The Senate yesterday summoned the National Security Adviser, Babagana Monguno, the Chief of Army Staff, Lt. General Tukur Buratai and all other security chiefs over the proliferation of fire arms in the country. Also summoned were the Director General of the Department of State Service (DSS) Lawal Daura, the Inspector General of Police, Ibrahim Idris, Comptroller - General of Customs, Hameed Ali and his immigration counterpart, Mohammed Babandede No date has been fixed for the appearance of the security chiefs. They are to appear before the Senate to proffer solutions to the challenge of proliferation of firearms. The Senate mandated its Committee on Intelligence and National Security to conduct a thorough investigation with a view to unravelling the remote and immediate causes of the proliferation of firearms in the country, as well as proffer a lasting solution to the problem. The resolutions followed a motion sponsored by Senator Suleiman Hunkuyi (APC, Kaduna). He said tribal, communal, religious and other sectarian clashes; including the farmers/herders crises were now more devastating due to wrongful and easy acquisition of firearms in the country. It emerged yesterday that the Inspector General of Police, Ibrahim Idris may appear today before the Senate over the arrest of Senator Dino Melaye (APC, Kogi) and killings in the country. Idris had twice shunned invitation of the Senate. On Monday, Saraki and the Speaker Yakubu Dogara reported the IGP to President Muhammadu Buhari during a meeting at the Presidential Villa. Saraki at the plenary while speaking on killings in Zamfara state said the IGP has been given today to appear before the Senate.